ce:section.ce:para:
To evaluate the antibacterial performance of CDs, we conducted a comprehensive evaluation of their MIC against two bacterial strains, Staphylococcus aureus(CICC10384)and E. coli(ML-35), through a series of two-fold dilutions (Table 1
                        ). Their MIC was calculated at concentrations of 39 μg/mL, 78.1 μg/mL, and 9.8 μg/mL for CDs1, CDs2, and CDs3, respectively, suggesting effective antibacterial properties against both bacterial strains. Subsequent evaluation of antibacterial kinetics revealed rapid entry of E. coli into the logarithmic phase, with Staphylococcus aureus transitioning to this phase following a 2-hour lag period (Fig. 5
                        ). Over the initial 14 h, both bacterial strains exhibited rapid proliferation, followed by a deceleration in growth rate, indicating entry into a stable growth phase. Upon introduction of CDs, a significant inhibition of exponential growth was observed, demonstrating substantial suppression of bacterial proliferation. CDs1, CDs2, and CDs3 effectively suppressed growth, with higher concentrations yielding stronger effects, aligning with MIC results and indicating concentration-dependent antibacterial efficacy.

To assess the detection capability of CDs1 across various substances, including antibiotics (CTC, OTC, and TC, florfenicol (FF), clarithromycin (CLARY), kanamycin sulfate (KM), neomycin sulfate (NS), and chloramphenicol (CAP)), common amino acids (phenylalanine (Phe), glycine (Gly), arginine (Arg), serine (Ser), and aspartic acid(Asp)), and multifarious metal ions (Fe3+, Sn2+, Ca2+, Cd2+, Cu2+, Hg2+, K
                        +, Mg2+, Mn2+, Na+, Ni2+, and Sr2+), each solution at concentrations of 100 μmol/L was treated with CDs1 solution. The fluorescence intensity of CDs1 was monitored at an excitation wavelength of 350nm. Remarkably, among all the tested substances, only tetracycline antibiotics, including CTC, OTC, and TC, induced a significant decrease in the fluorescence intensity of CDs1 (Fig. S4), demonstrating the high selectivity of CDs1 towards these particular tetracycline antibiotics. Subsequently, interference experiments were conducted by introducing the aforementioned selective particles (Ca2+, Cu2+, Mg2+, Na+, Ni2+, Phe, Gly, Arg, Ser, Asp, FF, CLARY, KM, NS, and CAP) into a mixed solution of CDs1 and tetracycline antibiotics (Fig. 8
                        ). Notably, the presence of other substances did not exert any discernible influence on the fluorescence of the mixed solution, indicative of CDs1′s resilience to interference. Therefore, CDs1 exhibited excellent anti-interference capabilities, thereby ensuring the accuracy and reliability of tetracycline antibiotic detection.

Subsequently, the fluorescence quenching response of CDs1 to tetracycline antibiotics was examined. A concentration gradient of tetracycline antibiotics was introduced into CDs1 solution, and the resulting fluorescence intensity of CDs1 was measured (Fig. 9
                        a-c). A successive decrease in the fluorescence intensity of CDs1 was observed with increasing concentrations of tetracycline antibiotics. Specifically, for CTC concentrations ranging from 0 to 20 μmol/L, 20 to 60 μmol/L, and 60 to 130 μmol/L, linear relationships were calculated as (F0 - F)/F0 = 0.01251 (CTC) - 0.01817 (R2 = 0.9951), (F0 - F)/F0 (CTC) = 0.00643 + 0.16504 (R2 = 0.9931), and (F0 - F)/F0 = 0.00341 (CTC) + 0.35819 (R2=0.9951), respectively (Fig. 9d).The detection limit for CTC was determined to be 0.18 μmol/L (3δ/k). Similarly, for OTC concentrations spanning from0 to 37.5 μmol/L, 37.5 to 90 μmol/L, and 90 to 150 μmol/L, the linear relationships were established as (F0 - F)/F0= 0.01515 [OTC] −0.00883 (R2= 0.99928), (F0-F)/F0=0.00442 [OTC]+ 0.40982 (R2=0.99398), and (F0-F)/F0= 0.002065 [OTC] + 0.6132 (R2=0.99463), respectively (Fig. 9e). The detection limit for OTC was established to be 0.15 μmol/L (3δ/k). Furthermore, for TC concentrations ranging from 0 to 25 μmol/L, 25 to 80 μmol/L, and 80 to 150 μmol/L, the linear relationship were determined as (F0 - F)/F0 = 0.01759 [TC] + 0.0089 (R2 = 0.99322), (F0 - F)/F0 = 0.00598 [TC] + 0.3115 (R2 = 0.99745), and (F0 - F)/F0 = 0.00305 [TC] + 0.5452 (R2=0.99306), respectively (Fig. 9f). The detection limit for TC was determined to be 0.13 μmol/L (3δ/k). All outcomes further exhibited the high selectivity and anti-interference capability of CDs1 towards tetracycline antibiotics. In addition, compared with previous studies (Table 2
                        ), the CDs1 exhibited a low detection limit and a broad detection range. The better sensing performances of CDs1 due to the capability of surface functionalities of CDs which to the possibility of specific binding with antibiotics.
